Recapping:

  • We initially expressed genotypic means, breeding value and genotypic variance as a function of allele frequencies and genotypic values
  • Using genetic designs we were able to distangle the causal variance components, using information from resemblance between relaties
  • We defined the basis to compute the heritability and its importance to compute the genetic gains

Plan for today:

  • Introduce multivariate models to estimate residual and genetic variances and covariances
  • Fit a model with different variance components for the residuals
  • Fit a multi-trait model

1 Theory

1.1 Introduction

Selection of in plant and animal breeding is usually based on a combination of several traits of economic importance. So far, we have analyzed traits individually using univariate models. After predicting the genetic values, we discussed that such can be combined using a selection index on which the individuals are ranked. In this section, we will modelling variance and covariance (var-cov) structures under two theorical approaches:

  1. Heterogeneous residual variance
  2. Multi-response or multi-trait analysis

1.2 Variance and Covariance Model Specifications

In plants and animal breeding, there are specific scenarios where the use of specific var-cov structures are essential. For example:

  • We first evaluated the cases where the covariance between individuals in a population is known a priori through the specification of a kinship matrix.
  • Another common scenario is when the residual of a linear model is not homogeneous and therefore ANOVA’s assumptions are not met. As a consequence a residual matrix with heterogeneous errors can be fitted.
  • In the case of spacial analysis, where there is a spacial dependency for the residual
  • Time serie analysis, where there is a temporal dependency for the residuals

1.2.1 Definition

Consider the following equation for a mixed linear model:

\[y = Xb + Za + e\] \[var(y)=V = ZGZ'+ R\]

By default the variance of random effects is \(G=I\sigma^2_u\) and the variance of residuals is \(R=I\sigma^2_e\). There are many variance-covariance functions used for different models:

Model Number Parameter DEscription asreml-R
Identity 1 Identical variation id
Diagonal M Heterogeneous variations diag
CS 2 Compound symmetry with homogeneous variance interation model
CS Het M+1 Compound symmetry with heterogeneous variance corh
AR1 M+1 First order autoregressive model ar1
Unstructured M(M+1)/2 Unstructured model us

1.3 Defining a Multivariate Model

As originally presented by Mrode (2014), the model for a multivariate analysis resembles a stack of the univariate models for each of the traits. For example, consider a multivariate analysis for two traits, with the following models for each trait:

\[y_1 = X_1b + Z_1a_1 + e_1\] \[y_2 = X_2b + Z_2a_2 + e_2\] \[ \begin{bmatrix} {y_1} \\ {y_2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {X_1} & {0}\\ {0} & {X_2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} {b_1} \\ {b_2} \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} {Z_1} & {0}\\ {0} & {Z_2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} {b_1} \\ {b_2} \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} {e_1} \\ {e_2} \end{bmatrix} \]

  • \(y_i\) = vector of observations for the ith trait;
  • \(b_i\) = vector of fixed effects for the ith trait;
  • \(a_i\) = vector of random animal effects for the ith trait;
  • \(e_i\) = vector of random residual effects for the ith trait;
  • \(X_i\) and \(Z_i\) = incidence matrices relating records of the ith trait to fixed and random animal effects.

The use of these equations will change the form of the residual (R) and the genetic (G) matrices. In the case of two traits, multivariate models can be used to estimate genetic an residuals components for each trait, as follow:

\[ var\begin{bmatrix} {a_1} \\ {a_2} \\ {e_1} \\ {e_2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {g_{11}A} & {g_{12}A} & {0} &{0} \\ {g_{21}A} & {g_{22}A} & {0} &{0} \\ 0 & 0 & {r_{11}} &{r_{12}} \\ 0 & 0 & {r_{21}} &{r_{22}} \\ \end{bmatrix} \] Same assumptions are more commonly reported as Kronecker product in the following way:

\[ G = \begin{bmatrix} {\sigma^2_{a_1}} & {\sigma^2_{a_{12}}} \\ {\sigma^2_{a_{12}}} & {\sigma^2_{a_{2}}} \end{bmatrix} \otimes A; R = I \otimes \begin{bmatrix} {\sigma^2_{e_1}} & {\sigma^2_{e_{12}}} \\ {\sigma^2_{e_{12}}} & {\sigma^2_{e_{2}}} \end{bmatrix} \]

The mixed model equation have a similar form that presented when the Animal Model was discussed:

\[ \begin{bmatrix} {X'R^{-1}X} & {X'R^{-1}Z} \\ {Z'R^{-1}X} & {Z'R^{-1}Z} + {A^{-1}G^{-1}} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} {\hat{b}}\\ {\hat{a}} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {X'R^{-1}y} \\ {Z'R^{-1}y} \end{bmatrix} \]

Advantages of multi-trait models:

  • Breeding values (EBVs) estimated from multivariate models for low heritability traits receive an increase in accuracy by exploiting their covariances with higher heritability traits.
  • Genetic correlation estimates via multivariate models are useful to understand how different traits are genetically related to fitness.
  • Increase in accuracy with multivariate analysis resulting from better connections in the data due to residual covariance between traits

2 Practice

  • Heterogeneous R variance structures in a coffee data set
  • Multi-trait model in a maize data set

2.1 Heterogeneous residual variance

  • Breeding and genetics experiments often have natural groupings of observations (such as environments, or ages of individuals, or years of evaluation) that may differ in terms of their error variation.
  • Such trends are mostly observed when the residual diagnostic is performed.

2.1.2 Defining the model

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + L_i + B(L)_{ij} + \underline{G_k} + \underline{GL_{ik}} + \underline{e_{ijk}}\]

  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean;
  • \(L_i\) = effect of year i
  • \(B(L)_{ij}\) = effect of block j nested within year i
  • \(G_k\) = random effect of genotype k, where \(G_{k} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_g)\)
  • \(GL_{ik}\) = random effect of interaction between genotype k and year i, where \(GL_{ik} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_{g \times e})\)

Residuals

  • Homogenous variance models

\[R=\sigma^2_eI_{476} = \sigma^2_ e \begin{bmatrix} {1} & \dots & {0}\\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ {0} & \dots & {1} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {\sigma^2_ e} & \dots & {0}\\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ {0} & \dots & {\sigma^2_ e} \end{bmatrix}\]

  • Heterogeneous R variance structures (diagonal structure)

\[R=\sigma^2_{e_i} R_j = \sigma^2_{e_i} \begin{bmatrix} {R_1} & {0} & {0} & {0}\\ {0} & {R_2} & {0} & {0}\\ {0} & {0} & {R_3} & {0}\\ {0} & {0} & {0} & {R_4}\\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {\sigma^2_{e1}I_{119}} & {0} & {0} & {0}\\ {0} & {\sigma^2_{e2}I_{119}} & {0} & {0}\\ {0} & {0} & {{\sigma^2_{e3}}I_{119}} & {0}\\ {0} & {0} & {0} & {{\sigma^2_{e4}}I_{119}}\\ \end{bmatrix}\]

Codes

# Coffee data set
#################
library(asreml)
library(dplyr)
library(asremlPlus)
coffee = read.csv("/home/lferrao/Dropbox/classes/2020/QuantitativeGenetics/week10_MultiTrait/coffee_FES_int.csv", h=T, colClasses = c("factor", "factor", "numeric", "numeric", "factor"))
head(coffee)
str(coffee)


coffee = coffee %>%
  mutate(MeanPlot = yield/Numb.Plants) # Mean value per plot

# Missing data
coffee %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(missing = sum(is.na(yield))) # more NA for the second year

# Plots
boxplot(coffee$MeanPlot~coffee$year)

# Models
m1 = asreml(MeanPlot ~  block%in%year + year,
        random= ~ trat+trat:year, 
        data=coffee)
summary(m1)$varcomp
plot(m1)

m2 = asreml(MeanPlot ~  block%in%year + year,
        random= ~ trat+trat:year, 
        residual=~dsum(~id(units)|year),
        data=coffee)
summary(m2)$varcomp
plot(m2)

# Goodness of fit
infoCriteria(m1)  # AIC, BIC
infoCriteria(m2)  # AIC, BIC

2.2 Multi-trait our multi-response model

  • Multivariate are complex models, in which multiple parameters are estimated at the same time – high computational demand.

  • A general pipeline is:
    • Standardize all response variables
    • Always start fitting single trait (univariate) models
    • Estimate the varcomp values in the single trait analysis – they are good starting values and can help in the multivariate version
    • In the multivariate version, start by testing a simple var-cov structures
    • Move to more complex VAR-COV models and check the %CPU used (it is common crash the system)

  • There are three traits for which we are interested in estimating variances and genetic correlations: days to pollen shed (pollen), days to silking (silking) and mean height of the five plants in each plot (height).
  • This model is an example where we can estimate the genotypic variances and covariances.

2.2.2 Defining the Model

Univariate version

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + L_i + \underline{B(L)_{ij}} + \underline{G_k} + \underline{GL_{ik}} + \underline{e_{ijk}}\]

  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean;
  • \(L_i\) = effect of location i
  • \(B(L)_{ij}\) = effect of block j nested within location i
  • \(G_k\) = effect of genotype k
  • \(GL_{ik}\) = effect of interaction between genotype k and location i
  • \(e_{ijk}\) = random effect error, distributed as: \(e_{ijk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_e)\)

Simplified matrix notation

\[y_i = X_i\beta_i + Z_iu_i + \varepsilon_i\]

\[ \begin{bmatrix} y_{1} \\ y_{2} \\ y_{3} \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} X_{1} &0 & ... & 0 \\ 0 & X_{2} & ...& 0 \\ 0& 0& ... & X_{3} \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \beta_{1} \\ \beta_{2} \\ \beta_{3} \\ \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} Z_{1} &0 & ... & 0 \\ 0 & Z_{2} & ...& 0 \\ 0& 0& ... & Z_{3} \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} u_{1} \\ u_{2} \\ u_{3} \\ \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} \varepsilon_1 \\ \varepsilon_2 \\ \varepsilon_3 \\ \end{bmatrix} \]

\[y|\beta, u, G_0, R_0 \sim \mathcal{N} (X\beta + Zu, R_0 \otimes I)\]

Codes

In this demo we will test four different model structures.

  1. m.height, m.silking and m.pollen are single trait (univariate) versions.

  2. m.diag: is a multi-trait version, where we a assume a simple var-cov (diag) for the genetic term and a complex structure (us) for the residual. Important: in this model we assume that traits are not genetically correlated.

\[ R_0= \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2_{e_1} & \sigma^2_{e_{12}} & \sigma^2_{e_{13}}\\ \sigma^2_{e_{21}} & \sigma^2_{e_2} & \sigma^2_{e_{23}}\\ \sigma^2_{e_{31}} & \sigma^2_{e_{32}} & \sigma^2_{e_{3}}\\ \end{bmatrix} ; G_0= \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2_{u_1} & 0 & 0\\ 0 & \sigma^2_{u_2} & 0\\ 0 & 0 & \sigma^2_{u_{3}}\\ \end{bmatrix} \]

  1. m.diag.init: same model as before, but using initial values. This is an alternative to improve software convergence

  2. m.us.init: we assume complex var-cov for the genetic and residual terms. Here, genetic correlations are computed between traits.

\[ R_0= \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2_{e_1} & \sigma^2_{e_{12}} & \sigma^2_{e_{13}}\\ \sigma^2_{e_{21}} & \sigma^2_{e_2} & \sigma^2_{e_{23}}\\ \sigma^2_{e_{31}} & \sigma^2_{e_{32}} & \sigma^2_{e_{3}}\\ \end{bmatrix} ; G_0= \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2_{u_1} & \sigma^2_{u_{12}} & \sigma^2_{u_{13}}\\ \sigma^2_{u_{21}} & \sigma^2_{u_2} & \sigma^2_{u_{23}}\\ \sigma^2_{u_{31}} & \sigma^2_{u_{32}} & \sigma^2_{u_{3}}\\ \end{bmatrix} \]

# Multi trait maize
###################
library(asreml)
maize = read.csv("/home/lferrao/Dropbox/classes/2020/QuantitativeGenetics/week10_MultiTrait/MaizeRILs.csv", h=T)
maize$rep = as.factor(maize$rep)
maize$RIL = as.factor(maize$RIL)

# Traits
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
hist(maize$pollen, main="pollen")
hist(maize$silking, main="silking")
hist(maize$height, main="height")

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Univariate Models
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##

# First univariate models
m.height = asreml(height ~location,
        random= ~ rep:location + RIL + RIL:location, 
        data=maize)

m.silking = asreml(silking ~location,
        random= ~ rep:location + RIL + RIL:location, 
        data=maize)

m.pollen = asreml(pollen ~location,
        random= ~ rep:location + RIL + RIL:location, 
        data=maize)

# Variance components
data.frame(height= summary(m.height)$varcomp[,1],
           pollen = summary(m.pollen)$varcomp[,1],
           silking = summary(m.silking)$varcomp[,1],
           row.names = rownames(summary(m.height)$varcomp))

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Multivariate Models
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##

# We should start with a relatively simple multivariate model
# Diagonal var-cov structure
# Trait effect is the multivariate version, it allows us to stack of the univariate models
# All fixed effects and random effects should involve an interaction with trait to create appropriate design matrices for the effects.

m.diag<-asreml(fixed=cbind(height,pollen,silking)~trait+trait:location,
                 random=~ diag(trait):RIL + 
                 diag(trait):(RIL:location) +
                 diag(trait):(rep:location),
               residual = ~id(units):us(trait),
                 data=maize)
var.comp = summary(m.diag)$varcomp

# G matrix for the traits (diagonal structure)
var.comp[grep("trait:RIL!",rownames(var.comp)),]

# s | 4.8   0    0  |
# p |  0    4.7  0  |
# h |  0    0   304 |

# We assumed no genetic correlations between traits

# Residual variance (unstructure structure)
var.comp[grep("units:trait!",rownames(var.comp)),]

# s | 3.3     1.0     -1.4   |
# p | 1.0     1.39     0.51  |
# h | -1.4    0.51     65    | 

# Diagonal: residual variances for height, pollen and silking. 
# Off-diag: residual correlations different traits 

# ---- # ---# 
# Observations:
# i) Convergence to globally optimal parameter values becomes more difficult
# ii) Choice of starting values becomes more important
# iii) The model requires estimates of 15 parameters. 6 only for the residual 
# vi) We did not standardized the traits (following book's example)

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Multivariate Models using initial values
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##

# As models become more complex, good initial values may be necessary to achieve convergence.
# We will use same model, but with initial values
# Initial values come from the univariate model

init.rep.loc<-c(13.44,0.44,0.66)
init.ril<-c(303.15,4.9,4.992)
init.ril.loc<-c(24.93, 0.573, 0.837)
init.res = c(64.9,0,1.179,0,0,2.89)

m.diag.init<-asreml(fixed=cbind(height,pollen,silking)~trait+trait:location,
                    random=~ diag(trait,init = init.ril):RIL + 
                            diag(trait,init = init.ril.loc):(RIL:location) +
                            diag(trait,init=init.rep.loc):(rep:location),
                    residual = ~id(units):us(trait,init=init.res),
                 data=maize)

var.comp.init = summary(m.diag.init)$varcomp
var.comp.init[grep("trait:RIL!",rownames(var.comp.init)),]
var.comp.init[grep("units:trait!",rownames(var.comp.init)),]

# Observations:
# i) No convergence problems
# ii) Initial values provided did not affect the result in this case.

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Multivariate Models using initial values
# Genetic Correlation
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##

# To model genetic correlations between traits, we need to change the var-cov of trait.RIL
# US (unstructure model)

init.rep.loc<-c(13.44,0.44,0.66)
init.ril.us<-c(303.15,0 ,4.9, 0, 0, 4.992)
init.ril.loc<-c(24.93, 0.573, 0.837)
init.res = c(64.9,0,1.179,0,0,2.89)

m.us.init<-asreml(fixed=cbind(height,pollen,silking)~trait+trait:location,
                    random=~ us(trait,init = init.ril.us):RIL + 
                            diag(trait,init = init.ril.loc):(RIL:location) +
                            diag(trait,init=init.rep.loc):(rep:location),
                    residual = ~id(units):us(trait,init=init.res),
                 data=maize)
m.us.init = update.asreml(m.us.init) # more iterations

var.comp.us = summary(m.us.init)$varcomp
var.comp.us[grep("trait:RIL!",rownames(var.comp.us)),]

# h | 303      23      21.5  |
# p |  23      4.9     4.28  |
# s |  21.5    4.28    5.08  |

# Difference between genetic and phenotypic correlation
m = matrix(c(303,23,21.5,
             23,4.9,4.28,
             21.5,4.28,5.08),nrow=3)
data.frame(cov2cor(m), 
           row.names = c("height", "pollen", "silking")) # genetic correlation
cor(maize[,c(9,6,7)]) # phenotypic correlation

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Goodness-of-fit
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
library(asremlPlus)
infoCriteria(m.diag)
infoCriteria(m.diag.init)
infoCriteria(m.us.init)

## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##
# Prediction
## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ## ----- ##

# Using height as one example

blups.univ = summary(m.height,coef=T)$coef.random
blups.mult = summary(m.us.init,coef=T)$coef.random

blups.mult.height = blups.mult[grep("trait_height",
                                    rownames(blups.mult)),] 

# std.error
head(blups.mult.height)
head(blups.univ)

tail(blups.mult.height)
tail(blups.univ) # in general, std errors are lower for the multi-trait model

# Prediction
cor(blups.mult.height[,1], blups.univ[,1])
plot(blups.mult.height[,1], blups.univ[,1])

2.2.3 Results and general comments

  • Even penalizing, the AIC values for the unstructure model is lower (better) than the other models, indicating that it is indeed best.

  • We introduced the function update.asreml that can be helpful to add more iteractions and hence active the convergence of complex models.

  • As more complex is the model, more important is the use of starting values.

  • Standardizing response variables is very important (although we did not use in this example).

  • Always start multivariate analysis with the simplest models.

  • In many cases it is complicated to model the residual and the genetic part at the same time (overparametrized models). In genetic studies, if possible, prioritize the genetic component by using simpler var-cov structures (eg, diag) for the residuals.

  • BLUPs predicted using univariate and multivariate versions are similar. Standard errors of predictions are lower from the multivariate model than the univariate model, since more information enters into the multivariate predictions

  • How to compute the \(h^2\) values? There are different alternatives. We will discuss more about that when we present the GxE models.

  • Is the correlation between BLUPs predicted via univariate version an estimate of genetic correlations between traits? No !!

3 Final Considerations

  • Heterogeneous residual variance is an alternative for experimental data that present temporal (time series) or spacial variation. This concept will be very important in the future when we discuss spatial analysis and specific var-cov structures for the residual.
  • Multivariate models are commonly used to estimate genetic correlations. Future GxE models used in this course can be seen as extension of these models
